  "why": "The paper describes applying fine-grained, in-memory pixel-level perturbations (e.g., Gaussian and multiplicative noise, 0.5% of pixels) and normalizes pixels to [0,1] for GAN training, but it does not describe enforcing serialized input-format constraints (such as clipping to [0,255] or rounding to integer pixel values) or generating inputs directly in a serialized format. Because the authors do not state any mechanism to ensure that small floating-point perturbations survive conversion/serialization, fault-inducing perturbations introduced in normalized or floating-point representations may be altered or lost when inputs are saved or represented in standard image formats. Under the metric guidance, this absence means failures induced by in-memory floating-point mutations may not be reproducible after serialization.",
